a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x :: real and f g :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. f x = 5 * x + 2"
and h1 : "\<forall> x. g x = 3 * x powr 2 - 4 * x"
shows  "f (f 1) - g (g 2) = 5"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Given $f(x)=5x+2$ and $g(x)=3x^2-4x$, evaluate $f(f(1))-g(g(2))$. The final Answer is 5
 ### Proof
 We have $f(1) = 5(1) + 2 = 7$, so $f(f(1)) = f(7) = 5(7) + 2 = 37$.
 We have $g(2) = 3(2)^2 - 4(2) = 3(4) - 8 = 4$, so $g(g(2)) = g(4) = 3(4)^2 -4(4) = 3(16) - 16 = 32$.
 Combining these, we have $f(f(1)) - g(g(2)) = 37-32 = \boxed{5}$.
 *)
